(5 points) Use the package caret to identify the optimal number of K. Run repeated k-fold cross validation. Use the accuracy for defining which number is the best. Do not forget to set seed

library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
## Loading required package: ggplot2
set.seed(1)
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
knn_s <- train(Top10~., data = songs, method = "knn", trControl = ctrl, preProcess = c("center", "scale"), tuneLength = 10)
knn_s$results

(8 points) Divide the data into Train (80% of cases) and Test (20% of cases) so that the distrubution of the variable Top10 does not change. Based on the results in the previous problem, choose the most optimal number of K. Run Knn classification using the package class saving predicted probabilities.

library(class)
set.seed(1)
index <- createDataPartition(songs$Top10, p = 0.8, list = F)
Train <- songs[index,]
Test <- songs[-index,]
knn_op <- knn(Train[, -34], Test[, -34], cl = Train$Top10, k = 23, prob = T)

(5 points) Solve the same classification problem using decision tree and plot the tree displaying the number of cases in each node,

library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
model <- rpart(Top10~., data = Train)
prp(model, type = 2, extra = 1, main = "Number of cases that fall in the node per calss")

(10 points) Build Confusion matrix for both models (knn and decision tree), compare and comment on all the accuracy measures. For knn use, both predicted classes and predicted probabilities in constructing the matrix.

Hint: when you use the predicted probabilities from the knn model, try to take different threshold values and comment what is the optimal one.(0.5 might not work,)

#PPV is 0.64516 which means that we predicted 64.5% of the songs were on the list of top10 songs and our prediction was right.
#NPV is 0.86312 which means that we predicted 86.3% of the songs were on the list of top10 songs and our prediction was wrong.

#According to my analysis, the best model is the decision tree which has 85.8% accuracy. This model also has a higher sensitivity than the KNN class model. The worst model is KNN probabilities as the accuracy is 25% and it is also less than the no information rate so it does not make any sense to use this model.

  worked overtime hasb't worked overtime  Sum

No 751 236 987 Yes 90 100 190 Sum 841 336 1177

no option option 1 option 2 option 3 Sum No 378 430 122 57 987 Yes 124 45 10 11 190 Sum 502 475 132 68 1177

#h_yes(overtime, no option) = P(overtime|yes) * P(no option|yes) * P(yes)
h_yes <- (90/190)*(124/190)*(190/1177)
h_yes
## [1] 0.04990386
#h_no(overtime, no option) = P(overtime|no) * P(no option|no) * P(no)
h_no <- (751/987)*(378/987)*(987/1177)
h_no
## [1] 0.2443645
#Predicted class label is No.
#P(no|overtime, no option) = h_yes/(h_yes+h_no)

Prob
